00:11:44,772 --> 00:11:47,375
It is possible, monk, said the Blessed One.

103
00:11:47,395 --> 00:12:00,613
Supposing, monk, there was a great stone mountain, a yojana long, and a yojana wide, and a yojana high, without holes or crevices, one solid mass of rock, a yojana seven miles approximately,

104
00:12:01,758 --> 00:12:17,826
at the end of every hundred years a man would stroke it once with a piece of cloth that great stone mountain might by this effort be worn away and eliminated before the eon would still not have come to an end so long is an eon

105
00:12:19,121 --> 00:12:39,509
and of eons of such length we have wandered through so many eons so many hundreds of eons so many thousands of eons so many hundreds of thousands of eons for what reason because monks this samsara is without discoverable beginning and then you get that repetition

106
00:12:39,642 --> 00:13:09,649
at first point is not discerned of beings roaming and wandering on hindered by ignorance and fettered by craving for such a long time you have experienced suffering anguish and disaster and swell the cemetery it is enough to become disenchanted with all formations enough to become dispassionate towards them enough to be liberated for them and I'm beginning to wonder why Bhikkhu Bodhi had so many of these collected he only needed one or two

107
00:13:09,629 --> 00:13:38,015
so here again this idea of time you see this idea of time of course there's what you might call scientific time or physical time like the time it takes for the sun for the earth to go around the sun something objective of that nature so we've got hours and years and all there's also psychological time see

108
00:13:37,995 --> 00:13:43,304
Remember that sometimes time seems to drag when we don't particularly enjoy it.

109
00:13:44,106 --> 00:13:46,350
And sometimes we wonder where the time went.

110
00:13:47,032 --> 00:13:48,274
Sometimes we don't get enough time.

111
00:13:48,695 --> 00:13:52,741
So there's also this business of time as a mental thing.

112
00:13:53,582 --> 00:14:02,197
Now, just as an aside, remember the mind is always projecting a future for us.

113
00:14:02,784 --> 00:14:07,433
So when we're happy, the mind presumes, that's how it's going to be forever.

114
00:14:07,815 --> 00:14:12,884
So when the stock markets rose, and they rose, and they rose, everybody thought, well, it's going to be forever.

115
00:14:14,947 --> 00:14:21,299
When you're in the other side, when you're in depression, the mind says, well, this is how it's always going to be.

116
00:14:21,567 --> 00:14:23,870
When you've got pain, this is how the mind's going to always be.

117
00:14:24,490 --> 00:14:30,158
So, really be careful of that because the mind is always fooling us.

118
00:14:30,177 --> 00:14:31,720
It's always creating a future.

119
00:14:32,520 --> 00:14:37,606
And it's always regretting or nostalgic for the past.

120
00:14:37,966 --> 00:14:40,289
The mind won't stay in the present.

121
00:14:40,549 --> 00:14:41,532
It doesn't like the present.

122
00:14:42,692 --> 00:14:46,317
Because it experiences the present as a sort of deadness.

123
00:14:47,379 --> 00:14:49,160
Like nothing happens in the now.

124
00:14:50,760 --> 00:14:53,663
If you're right in the now, nothing much happens.

125
00:14:54,024 --> 00:14:57,327
And if you're in the now, you don't know what's going to happen next.

126
00:14:57,347 --> 00:14:58,249
And that's too fearful.

127
00:15:00,171 --> 00:15:05,135
So the mind is always creating the next moment for us.

128
00:15:05,155 --> 00:15:06,537
Now that's what you're doing in meditation.

129
00:15:06,777 --> 00:15:09,679
You're watching how the mind is always creating the next eon.

130
00:15:12,842 --> 00:15:14,225
