158
00:18:02,944 --> 00:18:06,008
It is enough to become disenchanted with formations

159
00:18:06,493 --> 00:18:13,762
enough to become dispassionate towards them, enough to be liberated for them.

160
00:18:13,782 --> 00:18:30,325
And just as a final thing, modern science, which equates very much with the Buddhist understanding of the mind, this idea of the vacuum.

161
00:18:31,064 --> 00:18:38,998
which contains this unknowable energy, out of which the manifest universe seems to arise, the manifest and the unmanifest.

162
00:18:39,957 --> 00:18:50,671
And in Buddhist understanding there is this what you might call ground consciousness, the Nibbānic consciousness.

163
00:18:51,692 --> 00:19:01,105
And this Nibbānic consciousness finds itself in what you might call what we experience as the mind.

164
00:19:01,237 --> 00:19:12,833
And what we mean by mind is thoughts, images, emotions, and how the mind actually contacts the world physically, you know, light, etc., etc.

165
00:19:13,318 --> 00:19:19,387
And that, actually speaking, everything is coming out of that base nine.

166
00:19:19,949 --> 00:19:22,071
It's not the other way around.

167
00:19:22,913 --> 00:19:35,412
So, you could say that a materialist, looking only at matter, has to then find a way of explaining how consciousness arises from subatomic particles.

168
00:19:36,692 --> 00:19:37,253
And they can't.

169
00:19:37,535 --> 00:19:41,840
It's called a hard problem.

170
00:19:42,664 --> 00:19:45,508
But from a spiritual point of view, it's actually coming the other way.

171
00:19:46,087 --> 00:19:51,512
It's as though they're looking at the world at the wrong end of the telescope.

172
00:19:51,532 --> 00:20:05,185
It's actually coming out of this emptiness, this vacuum, which, within us, is this Nibbanic consciousness, the knowing, you see.

173
00:20:05,666 --> 00:20:09,009
